<body><p>GE.11 -14115
</p>
<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Seventeenth session 
</b>Agenda item 10 
<b>Technical assistance and capacity-building 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Nigeria (on behalf of the African Group): draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>  17/&#8230; Assistance to Somalia in the field of human rights 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council,  
</i></p>
<p><i> Guided</i> by the Charter of the United Nations and the Universal Declaration of 
Human Rights,  
</p>
<p><i> Acknowledging</i> that peace and security, development and human rights are the 
pillars of the United Nations system,  
</p>
<p><i> Reaffirming</i> its respect for the sovereignty, territorial integrity, political 
independence and unity of Somalia,  
</p>
<p><i> Recalling</i> Human Rights Council resolutions 5/1 and 5/2 of 18 June 2007, 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling</i> <i>also </i>previous Human Rights Council resolutions on the situation of 
human rights in Somalia and Council decision 14/119 of 18 June 2010,  
</p>
<p><i> Acknowledging</i> the commitment of and efforts made by the African Union and the 
African Union Mission in Somalia to support Somali-led efforts to achieve reconciliation 
and stability, and the efforts made by the international community and regional 
stakeholders to help Somalia re-establish stability, peace and security in its national 
territory,  
</p>
<p><i> Noting </i>the outcomes of the high-level consultative meeting, held in Nairobi on 12 
and 13 April 2011, the special meeting on Somalia of the Security Council, held in Nairobi 
on 25 May 2011 and the meeting of the International Contact Group on Somalia, held in 
Kampala on 2 and 3 June 2011,  
</p>
<p><i> Acknowledging</i> the constructive engagement of the Transitional Federal Government 
of Somalia and its subnational entities in the universal periodic review, and the decision of 
the Government to hold a special meeting of the Council of Ministers before the end of 
June 2011 to consider the acceptance by Somalia of numerous recommendations,  
</p>
<p><i> Deeply concerned</i> about the steep rise in the number of children under 5 years of age 
who have been wounded in Mogadishu since May 2011,  
</p>
<p><i> Recognizing</i> the unique challenges faced by the Government at the national and 
subnational levels in implementing these recommendations and its expressed desire to 
</p>

<p>receive additional technical support and assistance from the Office of the United Nations 
High Commissioner for Human Rights and any willing country, including through the work 
of the independent expert on the situation of human rights in Somalia, and from the 
independent consultant on the elaboration of the report of Somalia  under the universal 
periodic review mechanism,  
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Strongly condemns </i>the grave and systematic human rights violations 
perpetrated against the civilian population by Al-Shabab and like-minded terrorist groups;  
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Encourages</i> the Transitional Federal Government of Somalia and its 
subnational entities to consider favourably the recommendations presented during the 
review of Somalia by the Working Group on the Universal Periodic Review, and to 
implement them;  
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Decides</i> to renew the mandate of the independent expert on the situation of 
human rights in Somalia for a period of one year, from September 2011, with a view to: 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) Maximizing the much-needed provision and flow of tangible and timely 
technical assistance to Somalia in the field of human rights;  
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) Supporting the efforts of the Transitional Federal Government and its 
subnational entities to ensure respect for human rights, and supporting the Government in 
its work to complete the outstanding task of the transitional mandate; 
</p>
<p> 4.<i> Requests </i>the independent expert to evaluate the sufficiency and effectiveness 
of the technical assistance provided to Somalia for implementing the accepted 
recommendations, and to submit a comprehensive report thereon to the Human Rights 
Council at its eighteenth and nineteenth sessions;  
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Requests</i> the Office of the High Commissioner, through its East Africa 
Regional Office and the work of the independent expert, to provide the Government with 
the necessary resources and technical assistance at the national and subnational levels with 
a view to enhancing its capacity to implement the accepted recommendations, and to 
submit a report thereon to the Human Rights Council at its nineteenth session;  
</p>
<p> 6. <i>Requests</i> the Secretary-General and the Office of the High Commissioner to 
provide the independent expert with all the human, technical and financial assistance 
necessary to carry out his or her mandate;  
</p>
<p> 7. <i>Decides</i> to remain seized of the matter. 
</p>
<p>    </p>

